title: Grateful Dead Live at Fillmore West on 1970-04-09
lineage: [SBD > MR > Cass > D > CD] + [AUD > MC > 4x Cass > DAT > CD]
description: Good Morning Little School Girl, Mama Tried, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Viola Lee Blues Candyman, Friend Of The Devil, Deep Elem Blues, Black Peter, Uncle John's Band Good Lovin'-> Drums-> Good Lovin', Cowboy Song, It's A Man's World, Cryptical Envelopement-> Drums-> The Other One-> Cryptical Envelopement-> Me & My Uncle, Not Fade Away-> Turn On Your Love Light

reviews.review_text:
Grate Show! I wish I knew how to download these soundboards! I have Vista and am not really sure how to do it? Can anyone help? 
SwanSong_79@hotmail.com
1970 Fillmore West... Does it get much better?!
Very Nice The acoustic soundboard is of course sublime, and the audience portion is not too too bad. Very exciting Other One.
Love This Show! The Cowboy Song man! The Cowboy song.

A Very Strange & In & Out Show And as bad as it is, it is not so bad that I cannot award this version of this show a full 5 stars.

Whoever did this presentation has an extreme love for this music and for mankind, in general.
Cowboy --> Sugar Mags? Doesn't anyone else hear the so-called "cowboy" jam quoting Sugar Magnolia's riffs?

The first part is super high quality, and both Man's World and the cowboy thing are great. The rest of the tape sounds horrible, and a lot of the Dead's regular repertoire isn't played that well. I think they were a little bored; they hadn't yet morphed into the "never repeat a song in 2 consecutive shows" band they later became.

Not the right audio for this date Great show, but set list in description doesn't match these songs. Deadbase matches the description set list. Where's the show with Good Morning Little School Girl, Mama Tried, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider ? 

BTW, some audio issues in It's a mans world.

good dead It's A Man's World is excellent as is NFA. Whether Man's world is 4/9 is dubious. First set apprarently contained Schoolgirl, China Rider and Viola Lee Blues. Acoustic on down matches actual setlist. First electric set is basically unseen and a smoker.

Cool show; Amazing AUD recording I was really impressed with the AUD parts of this show.  A very nice job, particularly given how early it was.  Many thanks to all the folks who contributed to putting this together and making it available.  This is a treasure; they were so good during this period and so much of it doesn't survive.

Nice record of a fun sounding show Does anyone know where The Cowboy Song came from? It doesn't sound like something they went into while tuning and it doesn't seem like a song they would come up with in general. Were they on the bill with someone else that night who might have joined them onstage? It's definitely an oddity for the boys to just pull out. 

Friend of the Devil is also AUD for the first few minutes and then continues in a sweet SBD.

Cowboy Song Per Deadlists.com:

"Cowboy Song" is an Instrumental improvisation involving audience participation on a hoe-down type riff with an unknown vocalist conducting in a sort of scat & yodel fashion (it isn't Marmaduke or Ramblin Jack or David Bromberg -- maybe it's Nelson on acid?); this one-time-only affair never had a name -- the title comes from tape labels.
Set list correct The setlist here matches DeadBase 50, (See updates for this date on page 37.)
